Later , the public bars gradually improved until sometimes almost the only difference was in the prices , so that customers could choose between economy and exclusivity -LRB- or youth and age , or a jukebox or dartboard -RRB- .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB- While the names of saloon and public bar may still be seen on the doors of pubs , the prices -LRB- and often the standard of furnishings and decoration -RRB- are the same throughout the premises , and many pubs now comprise one large room .
However the modern importance of dining in pubs encourages some establishments to maintain distinct rooms or areas .
It was not only the wealthy visitors who would use these rooms .
The snug was for patrons who preferred not to be seen in the public bar .
Ladies would often enjoy a private drink in the snug in a time when it was frowned upon for women to be in a pub .
These are on a historic interiors list in order that they can be preserved .
It was the pub that first introduced the concept of the bar counter being used to serve the beer .
It became known as the public bar -LSB- citation needed -RSB- .
The other , more private , rooms had no serving bar -- they had the beer brought to them from the public bar .
There are a number of pubs in the Midlands or the North which still retain this set up but these days the beer is fetched by the customer from the taproom or public bar .
In the Manchester district the public bar was known as the `` vault '' , other rooms being the lounge and snug as usual elsewhere .
By the early 1970s there was a tendency to change to one large drinking room and breweries were eager to invest in interior design and theming .
These island bars became popular as they also allowed staff to serve customers in several different rooms surrounding the bar .
