Another very common arrangement was -LRB- and is -RRB- for the landlord to own the premises -LRB- whether freehold or leasehold -RRB- independently of the brewer , but then to take a mortgage loan from a brewery , either to finance the purchase of the pub initially , or to refurbish it , and be required as a term of the loan to observe the solus tie .
A trend in the late 20th century was for breweries to run their pubs directly , using managers rather than tenants .
The landlord of a tied pub may be an employee of the brewery -- in which case he/she would be a manager of a managed house , or a self-employed tenant who has entered into a lease agreement with a brewery , a condition of which is the legal obligation -LRB- trade tie -RRB- only to purchase that brewery 's beer .
The beer selection is mainly limited to beers brewed by that particular company .
This law has now been repealed but while in force it dramatically altered the industry .
Some pubs still offer a regularly changing selection of guest beers .
Pubs within a chain will usually have items in common , such as fittings , promotions , ambience and range of food and drink on offer .
A pub chain will position itself in the marketplace for a target audience .
One company may run several pub chains aimed at different segments of the market .
Local events were often commemorated in pub signs .
Some pub signs are in the form of a pictorial pun or rebus .
Interesting origins are not confined to old or traditional names , however .
Names and their origins can be broken up into a relatively small number of categories .
Pubs often have traditional names .
A common name is the `` Marquis of Granby '' .
