Bell was connected with the eugenics movement in the United States .
The committee unequivocally extended the principle to man .
From 1912 until 1918 he was the chairman of the board of scientific advisers to the Eugenics Record Office associated with Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory in New York , and regularly attended meetings .
Organisations such as these advocated passing laws -LRB- with success in some states -RRB- that established the compulsory sterilization of people deemed to be , as Bell called them , a `` defective variety of the human race . ''
By the late 1930s , about half the states in the U.S. had eugenics laws , and California 's compulsory sterilization law was used as a model for that of Nazi Germany .
