Modern standard Estonian has evolved on the basis of the dialects of Northern Estonia .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
In 1525 the first book published in the Estonian language was printed .
The New Testament was translated into southern Estonian in 1686 -LRB- northern Estonian , 1715 -RRB- .
The two languages were united based on northern Estonian by Anton thor Helle .
A fragment from Peterson 's poem `` Kuu '' expresses the claim reestablishing the birthright of the Estonian language :
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
The Russian language was termed as ` the language of friendship of nations ' and was taught to Estonian children , sometimes as early as in kindergarten .
Although teaching Estonian to non-Estonians in schools was compulsory , in practice learning the language was often considered unnecessary .
And again as in Latvia , today many of the remnant non-Estonians in Estonia have adopted the Estonian language ; about 40 % at the 2000 census .
The letters c , q , w , x and y are limited to proper names of foreign origin , and f , z , š , and ž appear in loanwords and foreign names only .
Ö and ü are pronounced similarly to their equivalents in Swedish and German .
The vowels Ä , Ö and Ü are clearly separate phonemes and inherent in Estonian , although the letter shapes come from German .
The letter õ denotes / ɤ / , unrounded / o / , or a close-mid back unrounded vowel .
It is almost identical to the Bulgarian ъ / ɤ̞ / and the Vietnamese ơ , and is used to transcribe the Russian ы .
Earlier writing in Estonian had by and large used an ad hoc orthography based on Latin and Middle Low German orthography .
Some influences of the standard German orthography -- for example , writing ` W ' / ` w ' instead of ` V ' / ` v ' persisted well into the 1930s .
Examples are the use of `` ya '' for '' ä '' -LRB- e.g. Pyarnu instead of Pärnu -RRB- , `` y '' instead of '' õ '' -LRB- e.g. , Pylva instead of Põlva -RRB- and `` yu '' instead of '' ü '' -LRB- e.g. , Pyussi instead of Püssi -RRB- .
Thus the illative for kollane maja -LRB- `` a yellow house '' -RRB- is kollasesse majja -LRB- `` into a yellow house '' -RRB- , but the terminative is kollase majani -LRB- `` as far as a yellow house '' -RRB- .
With respect to the Proto-Finnic language , elision has occurred ; thus , the actual case marker may be absent , but the stem is changed , cf. maja -- majja and the Pohjanmaa dialect of Finnish maja -- majahan .
The accusative coincides with the genitive in the singular and with nominative in the plural .
This is a rough equivalent of the perfective vs. imperfective aspect opposition .
The percentage of Low Saxon and High German loanwords can be estimated at 22 -- 25 percent , with Low Saxon making up about 15 percent .
