Although the word paper is etymologically derived from papyrus , the two are produced very differently and the development of the first is distinct from the development of the second .
This is accomplished by dissolving lignin in a cooking liquor , so that it may be washed from the cellulose ; this preserves the length of the cellulose fibres .
Most pulping operations using the kraft process are net contributors to the electricity grid or use the electricity to run an adjacent paper mill .
Another advantage is that this process recovers and reuses all inorganic chemical reagents .
In the TMP process , wood is chipped and then fed into large steam heated refiners , where the chips are squeezed and converted to fibres between two steel discs .
Mechanical pulping does not remove the lignin , so the yield is very high , > 95 % , however it causes the paper thus produced to turn yellow and become brittle over time .
Although large amounts of electrical energy are required to produce mechanical pulp , it costs less than the chemical kind .
On the paper machine the most common is the steam heated can dryer .
Paper at this point is uncoated .
-LRB- Uncoated papers are rarely suitable for screens above 150 lpi . -RRB-
Coated papers are divided into matte , semi-matte or silk , and gloss .
The fibres in the paper basically run in the machine direction .
Wove paper does not exhibit `` laidlines '' , which are small regular lines left behind on paper when it was handmade in a mould made from rows of metal wires or bamboo .
Handmade paper similarly exhibits `` deckle edges '' , or rough and feathery borders .
For example , a ream of 20 lb , 8.5 in × 11 in -LRB- 216 mm × 279 mm -RRB- paper weighs 5 pounds , because it has been cut from a larger sheet into four pieces .
In the United States , printing paper is generally 20 lb , 24 lb , or 32 lb at most .
1189 × 841 mm -RRB- .
Two sheets of A1 , placed upright side by side fit exactly into one sheet of A0 laid on its side .
Similarly , two sheets of A2 fit into one sheet of A1 and so forth .
Much of the early paper made from wood pulp contained significant amounts of alum , a variety of aluminium sulfate salts that is significantly acidic .
Early papermakers did not realize that the alum they added liberally to cure almost every problem encountered in making their product would eventually be detrimental .
The cellulose fibres that make up paper are hydrolyzed by acid , and the presence of alum would eventually degrade the fibres until the paper disintegrated in a process that has come to be known as `` slow fire '' .
The use of non-acidic additives to make paper is becoming more prevalent , and the stability of these papers is less of an issue .
Paper made from bleached kraft or sulfite pulps does not contain significant amounts of lignin and is therefore better suited for books , documents and other applications where whiteness of the paper is essential .
Paper made from wood pulp is not necessarily less durable than a rag paper .
The ageing behavior of a paper is determined by its manufacture , not the original source of the fibres .
Mass-market paperback books and newspapers tend to use mechanical papers .
Dioxins are highly toxic , and health effects on humans include reproductive , developmental , immune and hormonal problems .
They are known to be carcinogenic .
Some manufacturers have started using a new , significantly more environmentally friendly alternative to expanded plastic packaging .
