A treaty may also be known as an -LRB- international -RRB- agreement , protocol , covenant , convention , pact , or exchange of letters , among other terms .
For example , the Charter of the United Nations was `` DONE at the city of San Francisco the twenty-sixth day of June , one thousand nine hundred and forty-five . ''
Each of these treaties has seventeen parties .
These however are still bilateral , not multilateral , treaties .
The parties are divided into two groups , the Swiss -LRB- `` on the one part '' -RRB- and the EU and its member states -LRB- `` on the other part '' -RRB- .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
Treaties can also be amended informally by the treaty executive council when the changes are only procedural , technical change in customary international law can also amend a treaty , where state behavior evinces a new interpretation of the legal obligations under the treaty .
An example of a treaty requiring such legislation would be one mandating local prosecution by a party for particular crimes .
Hence , nations can be very careful about terming an agreement to be a treaty .
Many treaties expressly forbid withdrawal .
Consequently , withdrawal was not possible .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
An advantage of such an arbiter is that it prevents a party from prematurely and perhaps wrongfully suspending or terminating its own obligations due to another 's alleged material breach .
Other treaties may self-terminate if the treaty is meant to exist only under certain conditions .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
Stillman and Watt deny the authenticity of al-Waqidi .
Al-Waqidi has been frequently criticized by Muslim writers , who claim that he is unreliable .
It seems that no treaty has ever actually been invalidated on this provision .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
In the United States , the term `` treaty '' has a different , more restricted legal sense than exists in international law .
United States law distinguishes what it calls treaties from executive agreement , congressional-executive agreements , and sole executive agreements .
Some treaties grant the President the authority to fill in the gaps with executive agreements , rather than additional treaties or protocols .
