The grains are now washed in a process known as `` sparging '' .
This washing allows the brewer to gather as much of the fermentable liquid from the grains as possible .
The process of filtering the spent grain from the wort and sparge water is called wort separation .
Some modern breweries prefer the use of filter frames which allow a more finely ground grist .
A mixture of starch sources may be used , with a secondary starch source , such as maize -LRB- corn -RRB- , rice or sugar , often being termed an adjunct , especially when used as a lower-cost substitute for malted barley .
Some beers today , such as Fraoch ' by the Scottish Heather Ales company and Cervoise Lancelot by the French Brasserie-Lancelot company , use plants other than hops for flavouring .
