The characters encoded are numbers 0 to 9 , lowercase letters a to z , uppercase letters A to Z , basic punctuation symbols , control codes that originated with Teletype machines , and a space .
For example , lowercase j would become binary 1101010 and decimal 106 .
Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase .
Even more importantly , forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set -LRB- as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1 -RRB- will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged .
On some systems Control-S retains its meaning but Control-Q is replaced by a second Control-S to resume output .
DEC operating systems -LRB- OS/8 , RT-11 , RSX-11 , RSTS , TOPS-10 , etc. -RRB- used both characters to mark the end of a line so that the console device -LRB- originally Teletype machines -RRB- would work .
