It is a significant fact that the first use of asphalt by the ancients was in the nature of a cement for securing or joining together various objects , and it thus seems likely that the name itself was expressive of this application .
From the Greek , the word passed into late Latin , and thence into French -LRB- asphalte -RRB- and English -LRB- `` asphaltum '' and `` asphalt '' -RRB- .
In American English , asphalt -LRB- or asphalt cement -RRB- is the carefully refined residue from the distillation process of selected crude oils .
Another archaic term for asphalt/bitumen is `` pitch '' .
