Dutch dialects and regional languages are not spoken as often as they used to be .
The different dialects show many sound shifts in different vowels -LRB- even shifting between diphthongs and monophthongs -RRB- , and in some cases consonants also shift pronunciation .
As a result , when West Flemish try to talk Standard Dutch , they 're often unable to pronounce the g-sound , and pronounce it similar to the h-sound .
Next to sound shifts , there are ample examples of suffix differences .
Often simple suffix shifts -LRB- like switching between - the , - ske , - ke , - je , ... -RRB- , sometimes the suffixes even depend on quite specific grammar rules for a certain dialect .
Again taking West Flemish as an example .
Some Flemish dialects are so distinct that they might be considered as separate language variants , although the strong significance of language in Belgian politics would prevent the government from classifying them as such .
-LRB- West -RRB- Frisian evolved from the same West Germanic branch as Old English and is less akin to Dutch .
Though Belgium as a whole is multilingual , the two regions into which the country is divided -LRB- Flanders , francophone Wallonia , bilingual Brussels and small ` facility ' zones -RRB- are largely monolingual .
The Netherlands and Belgium produce the vast majority of music , films , books and other media written or spoken in Dutch .
As a foreign language , Dutch is mainly taught in primary and secondary schools in areas adjacent to the Netherlands and Flanders .
Each year , some 1,500 to 2,000 students take Dutch courses there .
In total , several thousand Indonesians study Dutch as a foreign language .
Owing to centuries of Dutch rule in Indonesia , many old documents are written in Dutch .
Unlike other European nations , the Dutch chose not to follow a policy of language expansion amongst the indigenous peoples of their colonies .
Yet the Indonesian language inherited many words from Dutch : words for everyday life as well as scientific and technological terms .
These account for some of the differences in vocabulary between Indonesian and Malay .
A further twenty-four percent of the population speaks Dutch as a second language .
Elsewhere in the world , the number of people learning Dutch is relatively small .
Unlike other Germanic languages , Dutch does n't have phonological aspiration of consonants .
Like most Germanic languages , the Dutch consonant system did not undergo the High German consonant shift and has a syllable structure that allows fairly complex consonant clusters .
One feature or the other may be considered redundant , and some phonemic analyses prefer to treat it as an opposition of tenseness .
However , even if not considered part of the phonemic opposition , the long/tense vowels are still realised as phonetically longer than their short counterparts .
