Czech influence on Slovak was protested by Slovak scholars , and when Slovakia broke off from Czechoslovakia in 1938 as the Slovak State -LRB- which then aligned with Nazi Germany in World War II -RRB- literary Slovak was deliberately distanced from Czech .
Since then , `` Czechoslovak '' refers to improvised pidgins of the languages which have arisen from the decrease in mutual intelligibility .
These missionaries , Constantine and Methodius , helped to convert the Czechs from traditional Slavic paganism to Christianity and established a church system .
This language , later known as Proto-Czech , was beginning to separate from its fellow West Slavic hatchlings Proto-Slovak , Proto-Polish and Proto-Sorbian .
Among other features , Proto-Czech was marked by its ephemeral use of the voiced velar fricative consonant -LRB- / ɣ / -RRB- and consistent stress on the first syllable .
Here , early Czech literature -LRB- a biblical translation , hymns and hagiography -RRB- flourished .
Old Czech texts , including poetry and cookbooks , were produced outside the university as well .
The Czechs became serfs ; Bohemia 's printing industry -LRB- and its linguistic and political rights -RRB- were dismembered , removing official regulation and support from its language .
Changes include the morphological shift of í to ej and é to í -LRB- although é survives for some uses -RRB- and the merging of í and the former ejí .
Changes during this time included spelling reform -LRB- notably , í in place of the former j and j in place of g -RRB- , the use of t -LRB- rather than ti -RRB- to end infinitive verbs and the non-capitalization of nouns -LRB- which had been a late borrowing from German -RRB- .
These changes differentiated Czech from Slovak .
In the 2000 United States Census , Czech was reported as the most-common language spoken at home -LRB- besides English -RRB- in Valley , Butler and Saunders Counties , Nebraska and Republic County , Kansas .
During the second half of the twentieth century , Czech dialect use began to weaken .
Increased travel and media availability to dialect-speaking populations has encouraged them to shift to -LRB- or add to their own dialect -RRB- standard Czech .
They are / a / , / ɛ / , / ɪ / , / o / , and / u / , their long counterparts / aː / , / ɛː / , / iː / , / oː / and / uː / , and three diphthongs , / ou̯ / , / au̯ / and / ɛu̯ / .
The latter two diphthongs and the long / oː / are exclusive to loanwords .
In all words of more than two syllables , every odd-numbered syllable receives secondary stress .
The first slot must contain a subject and object , a main form of a verb , an adverb or a conjunction -LRB- except for the light conjunctions a , `` and '' , i , `` and even '' or ale , `` but '' -RRB- .
The genitive case marks possessive nouns and some types of movement .
The remaining cases -LRB- instrumental , locative , vocative and dative -RRB- indicate semantic relationships , such as secondary objects , movement or position -LRB- dative case -RRB- and accompaniment -LRB- instrumental case -RRB- .
When Czech children learn their language 's declension patterns , the cases are referred to by number :
With few exceptions , feminine nouns in the nominative case end in - a , - e , or - ost ; neuter nouns in - o , - e , or - í , and masculine nouns in a consonant .
The Czech koruna is an example of this feature ; it is shown here as the subject of a hypothetical sentence , and declined as genitive for numbers five and up .
Most verbs are part of inflected aspect pairs -- for example , koupit -LRB- perfective -RRB- and kupovat -LRB- imperfective -RRB- .
This is distinct from past and present tense , and any Czech verb of either aspect can be conjugated into any of its three tenses .
The most common prefixes are na - , o - , po - , s - , u - , vy - , z - and za - .
The verb jít -LRB- to go -RRB- has the iterative form chodit -LRB- to go repeatedly -RRB- and the frequentative form chodívat -LRB- to go regularly -RRB- .
It is the form found in dictionaries and the form that follows auxiliary verbs -LRB- for example , můžu tě slyšet -- `` I can hear you '' -RRB- .
This mood indicates possible events , expressed in English as `` I would '' or `` I wish '' .
The háček -LRB- ˇ -RRB- is used with certain letters to form new characters : š , ž , and č , as well as ň , ě , ř , ť , and ď -LRB- the latter five uncommon outside Czech -RRB- .
The last two letters are sometimes written with a comma above -LRB- ʼ , an abbreviated háček -RRB- because of their height .
Writing of ordinal numerals is similar to most European languages .
The Czech language uses a decimal comma instead of a decimal point .
When writing a long number , spaces between every three numbers -LRB- e.g. between hundreds and thousands -RRB- may be used for better orientation in handwritten texts , but not in decimal places , like in English .
The number 1,234,567.8910 may be written as 1234567,8910 or 1 234 567,8910 .
