These socioeconomic factors are also significant to the limits of racial lines , because a minority of pardos , or brown people , are likely to start declaring themselves white or black if socially upward , and being seen as relatively `` whiter '' as their perceived social status increases -LRB- much as in other regions of Latin America -RRB- .
Thus , the historical construction of race in Brazilian society dealt primarily with gradations between persons of majoritarily European ancestry and little minority groups with otherwise lower quantity therefrom in recent times .
In the diverse geographic context of Europe , ethnicity and ethnic origin are arguably more resonant and are less encumbered by the ideological baggage associated with `` race '' .
France has developed an approach to dealing with ethnic problems that stands in contrast to that of many advanced , industrialized countries .
This means that it targets virtually no policies directly at racial or ethnic groups .
Instead , it uses geographic or class criteria to address issues of social inequalities .
It has , however , developed an extensive anti-racist policy repertoire since the early 1970s .
Until recently , French policies focused primarily on issues of hate speech -- going much further than their American counterparts -- and relatively less on issues of discrimination in jobs , housing , and in provision of goods and services .
To be White one had to have perceived `` pure '' White ancestry .
The one-drop rule or hypodescent rule refers to the convention of defining a person as racially black if he or she has any known African ancestry .
This rule meant that those that were mixed race but with some discernible African ancestry were defined as black .
The types of practices that take place under this new color-blind racism is subtle , institutionalized , and supposedly not racial .
He also states that many biological anthropologists see races as real yet `` not one introductory textbook of physical anthropology even presents that perspective as a possibility .
