In Italian a tent pole is known as l'antenna centrale , and the pole with the wire was simply called l'antenna .
Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as aerials or terminals .
It is typically connected to the inner conductor of a coaxial transmission line -LRB- or a matching network -RRB- ; the shield of the transmission line is connected to ground .
Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive ground , a so-called grounding structure may be employed to provide a better ground contact to the earth or which itself acts as a ground plane to perform that function regardless of -LRB- or in absence of -RRB- an actual contact with the earth .
This can be accomplished in many different ways leading to a plethora of antenna designs .
The increased power in the desired direction is at the expense of that in the undesired directions .
These elements are often identical .
The dipole antennas composing it are all considered `` active elements '' since they are all electrically connected together -LRB- and to the transmission line -RRB- .
The Yagi antenna has similar looking parasitic dipole elements but which act differently due to their somewhat different lengths .
There may be a number of so-called `` directors '' in front of the active element in the direction of propagation , and usually a single -LRB- but possibly more -RRB- `` reflector '' on the opposite side of the active element .
For reception , a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity .
With a vertical antenna a loading coil at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance ; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose .
One side of the feedline from the receiver or transmitter is connected to the rod , and the other side to the ground plane , which may be the Earth .
The ground waves used for broadcasting at low frequencies must be vertically polarized , so large vertical monopole antennas are used for broadcasting in the MF , LF , and VLF bands .
Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor -LRB- or element -RRB- , or pair of such elements , each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length -LRB- an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant -RRB- .
Fortunately at higher frequencies -LRB- UHF , microwaves -RRB- trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required .
If the conductor is 1⁄4 of a wavelength long , current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor , reflect through 180 degrees , and then another 90 degrees as it travels back .
The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant .
This process creates a standing wave in the conductor , with the maximum current at the feed .
The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole , a single 1⁄4 - wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane -LRB- or counterpoise -RRB- .
Thus , an antenna element is also resonant when its length is 3⁄4 of a wavelength .
This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points .
This is the ideal situation , because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input , producing the highest possible efficiency .
They are particularly common on radar systems , where the same antenna is used for both broadcast and reception , or for radio and television broadcasts , where the antenna is working with a single frequency .
A half-wave dipole has an effective area of 0.13 2 .
If more performance is needed , one can not simply make the antenna larger .
Although this would intercept more energy from the signal , due to the considerations above , it would decrease the output significantly due to it moving away from the resonant length .
Electrically this forms a single 1⁄2 - wavelength element .
Any varying electrical current , like the standing wave in the element , will radiate a signal .
In this case , aside from resistive losses in the element , the rebroadcast signal will be significantly similar to the original signal in both magnitude and shape .
If this element is placed so its signal reaches the main dipole in-phase , it will reinforce the original signal , and increase the current in the dipole .
The end closer to the source is referred to as the front .
Near the rear is a single active element , typically a half-wave dipole or folded dipole .
However , this also makes it increasingly sensitive to changes in frequency ; if the signal frequency changes , not only does the active element receive less energy directly , but all of the passive elements adding to that signal also decrease their output as well and their signals no longer reach the active element in-phase .
For this reason , reflectors often take the form of wire meshes or rows of passive elements , which makes them lighter and less subject to wind .
In some cases the physical length of the antenna can be `` trimmed '' to obtain a pure resistance .
Instead , it is often desired to have an antenna whose impedance does not vary so greatly over a certain bandwidth .
Making the element using a tube of a diameter perhaps 1/50 of its length , however , results in a reactance at this altered frequency which is not so great , and a much less serious mismatch which will only modestly damage the antenna 's net performance .
On the other hand , amateur radio antennas need to operate over several bands which are widely separated from each other .
Most of the transmitter 's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high -LRB- reactive -RRB- impedance and draw little current from the same voltage .
A popular solution uses so-called traps consisting of parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks along each antenna element .
When used at one particular frequency band the trap presents a very high impedance -LRB- parallel resonance -RRB- effectively truncating the element at that length , making it a proper resonant antenna .
Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna 's radiation pattern .
This dimensionless ratio is usually expressed logarithmically in decibels , these units are called `` decibels-isotropic '' -LRB- dBi -RRB-
An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones .
It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2 / 4π , the wavelength squared divided by 4π .
The axis through the main lobe is called the `` principal axis '' or `` boresight axis '' .
A SWR of 1:1 is ideal .
A SWR of 1.5:1 is considered to be marginally acceptable in low power applications where power loss is more critical , although an SWR as high as 6:1 may still be usable with the right equipment .
In order to radiate 100 W of power , one would need to use a transmitter capable of supplying 125 W to the antenna .
If an SWR meter reads 150 W of incident power and 50 W of reflected power , that means that 100 W have actually been absorbed by the antenna -LRB- ignoring transmission line losses -RRB- .
Fortunately the loss resistance of antenna conductors such as aluminum rods can be calculated and the efficiency of an antenna using such materials predicted .
If an rms current I is delivered to the terminals of an antenna , then a power of I2Rr will be radiated and a power of I2Rloss will be lost as heat .
The power that an antenna will deliver to a receiver -LRB- with a proper impedance match -RRB- is reduced by the same amount .
In some receiving applications , the very inefficient antennas may have little impact on performance .
Consequently , an antenna with a 20 dB loss -LRB- due to inefficiency -RRB- would have little impact on system noise performance .
This is likewise true for a receiving antenna at very high -LRB- especially microwave -RRB- frequencies , where the point is to receive a signal which is strong compared to the receiver 's noise temperature .
However , in the case of a directional antenna used for receiving signals with the intention of rejecting interference from different directions , one is no longer concerned with the antenna efficiency , as discussed above .
An antenna 's linear polarization is generally along the direction -LRB- as viewed from the receiving location -RRB- of the antenna 's currents when such a direction can be defined .
For instance , a vertical whip antenna or Wi-Fi antenna vertically oriented will transmit and receive in the vertical polarization .
Even when the antenna system has a vertical orientation , such as an array of horizontal dipole antennas , the polarization is in the horizontal direction corresponding to the current flow .
Two special cases are linear polarization -LRB- the ellipse collapses into a line -RRB- as we have discussed above , and circular polarization -LRB- in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal -RRB- .
In circular polarization , the electric field -LRB- and magnetic field -RRB- of the radio wave rotates at the radio frequency circularly around the axis of propagation .
Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the `` thumb in the direction of the propagation '' rule .
Note that for circular polarization , optical researchers use the opposite right hand rule from the one used by radio engineers .
In some cases this is done in a more extreme manner , not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance , but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation .
-LSB- citation needed -RSB-
So an additional problem beyond canceling the unwanted reactance is of matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line .
Matching networks using discrete inductors and capacitors will have losses associated with those components , and will have power restrictions when used for transmitting .
This makes them inefficient as transmitting antennas .
The antenna 's height above the ground , as well as the electrical properties -LRB- permittivity and conductivity -RRB- of the ground , can then be important .
The phase of reflection of electromagnetic waves depends on the polarization of the incident wave .
On the other hand , the vertical component of the wave 's electric field is reflected at grazing angles of incidence approximately in phase .
The dielectric constant and conductivity -LRB- or simply the complex dielectric constant -RRB- is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency .
However it is often assumed that there is an advantage in an antenna having a high Q .
After all , Q is short for `` quality factor '' and a low Q typically signifies excessive loss -LRB- due to unwanted resistance -RRB- in a resonant L-C circuit .
However this understanding does not apply to resonant antennas where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance , a desired quantity which removes energy from the resonant element in order to radiate it -LRB- the purpose of an antenna , after all ! -RRB-
.
These two antennas will perform equivalently at the resonant frequency , but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the `` hi-Q '' antenna consisting of a thin conductor .
This is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies .
